# Service models

**How much of the stack you still own** after you rent from AWS. Three levels — each hands more to the provider, trading **flexibility for less operational burden**.

## IaaS — Infrastructure as a Service

AWS runs the **hardware, networking, virtualization**. *You* run the **OS, runtime, app, and data**. Most control, most work.
→ **EC2, EBS, VPC**

## PaaS — Platform as a Service

AWS also runs the **OS + runtime**. You bring only the **app + data** — no servers to patch.
→ **Elastic Beanstalk, RDS**

## SaaS — Software as a Service

AWS runs the **entire stack**. You just **use the app** and own **your data** inside it.
→ **WorkMail, Chime, QuickSight**

**No single "best" level — pick per workload:** raw control (IaaS) ⟷ zero ops (SaaS).
